801	7813504	Interaction Designer - Product	New York, NY	<div style="text-align: center;"><strong>Interaction Designer (Product) at Big-Time Video Tool Tech Leader/Shop</strong><br />\n <br />\nProactive.<br />\nPassionate.<br />\nStrategic.<br />\nDo these words describe you?<br />\n <br />\nThen you’ll be happy to know that a big-time tech leader wants someone just like you—an <strong>Interaction Designer</strong> with more than 3 years of experience designing web products to oversee design of interaction models for products that millions of users engage with every day.<br />\n <br />\nWorking side-by-side with a UX Researcher and Product Designer, you’ll own the design of all products you’re assigned to. Your mandate is to help the team design and develop interaction models for products that don’t simply function, but that touch users on an emotional level. You want them bawling, shouting, or laughing at their screens! <br />\n <br />\nFlexibility is key here. Be proactive when working by yourself. But with teammates—not just designers and product managers, but developers, too—you’ll need to keep an open mind about their contributions and value feedback on yours. You’ll have to demonstrate you’ve worked collaboratively before, but also show that you’re comfortable articulating—clearly—your design decisions. No one wants to work with a wet noodle!<br />\n <br />\nMore specifically, you’ll manage the visual design language, patterns, and assets for all your web and mobile application projects. That includes iteration, sketching, and prototyping user-centric solutions. And you’ll be asked to contribute your talents to those projects you’re not assigned to. For every product initiative, you’ll also need to advocate for standard design principles—usability, rich user experience, and clear and elegant interaction. The ultimate, bottom-line requirement? Deliver beautiful, functional, application front-end experiences in an agile environment.<br />\n <br />\nThe company is looking for someone with: deep knowledge of responsive web design, mad skills in visual as well as <strong>kinematic</strong> (how things move) aspects of UI design; expertise in standard web design tools—Sketch, Photoshop, Illustrator, Invision/Marvel, and Proto.io/Principle; and HTML and CSS. No need for actual coding experience, but you do have to know what’s code-able. Web development knowledge could help, too, but lack of it won’t hurt.<br />\n <br />\nSince you’ll be working so closely with researchers, you must be able to incorporate research—and product—data into your design processes. Be sure to demonstrate your ability to create systematic design experiences for wildly different customer interactions and needs via a robust and defined user experience. Show, too, that you are both resourceful and flexible about scalable and seamless web experiences. Oh, and a great interaction design portfolio helps, too!</div>	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Closed	2016-07-13 20:00:18.024724	2016-10-21 00:00:09.819186	Animoto	In-house	t	UX Design, Product Design, UI Design, Interaction Design
